The '''Open Handset Alliance''' ('''OHA''') is a [[consortium]] of 84<ref>[http://www.openhandsetalliance.com/oha_faq.html Alliance FAQ | Open Handset Alliance]</ref> firms to develop [[open standard]]s for [[mobile devices]]. Member firms include [[Google]], [[HTC Corporation|HTC]], [[Sony]], [[Dell]], [[Intel]], [[Motorola]], [[Qualcomm]], [[Texas Instruments]], [[Samsung Electronics]], [[LG Electronics]], [[T-Mobile]], [[Nvidia]], and [[Wind River Systems]].<ref name="AndroidAnnouce">{{cite web|url=http://www.openhandsetalliance.com/press_110507.html|title=Industry Leaders Announce Open Platform for Mobile Devices|accessdate=2007-11-05|date=2007-11-05|publisher=Open Handset Alliance}}</ref>
==History== The OHA was established on 5 November 2007, led by [[Google]] with 34 members including mobile handset makers, [[application software|application]] developers, some mobile carriers and chip makers.<ref name="companies">{{cite web|url=http://www.openhandsetalliance.com/oha_members.html|title=Open Handset Alliance members page|date=2007-11-05|accessdate=2007-11-05|publisher=Open Handset Alliance}}</ref> [[Android (operating system)|Android]], the flagship software of the alliance, is based on an open source license and competes against mobile platforms from [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[Microsoft]], [[Nokia]], [[Sony Ericsson]], ([[Symbian]]), [[Hewlett-Packard|HP]] (formerly [[Palm, Inc.|Palm]]), [[Research In Motion]], and [[Samsung Electronics]] ([[Bada (operating system)|bada]]).
==Products== At the same time as the announcement of the formation of the Open Handset Alliance on November 5, 2007, the OHA also unveiled [[Android (operating system)|Android]], an [[open source]] [[mobile phone]] [[platform (computing)|platform]] based on the [[Linux]] kernel.<ref name=AndroidAnnouce/> An early look at the [[SDK]] was released to developers on 12 November 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openhandsetalliance.com/developers.html|title=Developers|date=2007-11-05|accessdate=2007-11-05|publisher=Open Handset Alliance}}</ref>
The first commercially available phone running Android was the [[HTC Dream]] (also known as the T-Mobile G1). It was approved by the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) on 18 August 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.engadget.com/2008/08/18/htc-dream-fcc-approved-android-clear-for-launch/|title=FCC Approved HTC Dream|date=2008-08-18|publisher=Engadget}}</ref> and became available on 22 October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94982690|title=Google Is Calling. Will You Answer?}}</ref>
